description.plain: Certainly the most popular of Phil Spector’s artists, the Ronettes were named for and led by Veronica “Ronnie” Spector (nee Bennett). From their trademark hairdos to their iconic vocal talents, the Ronettes were the perfect vehicle for Spector’s innovative production techniques, and trailblazed a new era of pop with their singles and LP.

songs.title: Be My Baby

description.plain:
Released in August 1963, “Be My Baby” is the most famous song of The Ronettes and perhaps one of the most popular songs of the sixties.

The song was inducted to the Grammy Hall of Fame in 1999 and Rolling Stone listed it as the 22nd best song of all time.



“Be My Baby” is one of the main and finest examples of Ronette’s member Ronnie’s husband Phil Spector’s ‘Wall of Sound’ production, which consists on a large-scale recording of multiple session musicians to create an orchestra-type of sound that garnishes the instrumental of the song. Another exemple of this type of production can be found on one the band’s most famous songs, the Christmas hit “Sleigh Ride”.

songs.full_title: Sleigh Ride by The Ronettes
songs.title: Sleigh Ride

description.plain:
“Sleigh Ride” was originally composed in 1946 by Leroy Anderson. The Ronettes' cover, released in 1963, has become the best-known version of the song.

In his 2004 book Leroy Anderson: A Bio-Bibliography, Steve Metcalf says:

“Sleigh Ride” […] has been performed and recorded by a wider array of musical artists than any other piece in the history of Western music.

songs.full_title: Baby I Love You by The Ronettes
songs.title: Baby I Love You

description.plain:
“Baby, I Love You” is a pop song written by Jeff Barry, Ellie Greenwich, and Phil Spector, produced by Spector, and appears on the Ronettes' debut album, Presenting the Fabulous Ronettes.



Since the other two Ronettes were unavailable for recording due to being on tour with Dick Clark, the lead vocals were soley Ronnie’s. The instrumentation was done by The Wrecking Crew, and the backing vocals were sung by Cher.
